@node features "Features"

Features

      - Outputs a reminder consisting of a user-supplied
        text string following a user-defined time interval

      - Time interval can be based on either a:

           -- Standard clock (HH:MM AM/PM), or

           -- Duration (HH:MM:SS)

      - Reminder can be:

           -- A Workbench screen-based pop-up window 
              with optional Workbench screen flash

           -- Spoken via the AmigaDOS "Say" command
              (see "Requirements")

           -- Both the above

      - Spoken reminder is tunable as follows:

           -- Choice of Male/Female/Natural/Monotone voice

           -- Selectable speed

           -- Selectable pitch

           -- Test button allows you to hear the spoken reminder
              so you can checkout your "tuning" prior to committing
              the reminder

      - Gadtools user-interface

      - Tested OK using the Enforcer

@endnode

@node requirements "Requirements"

Requirements

      - AmigaDOS 2.04(+) 

      - 68000(+) CPU

      - To utilize the spoken reminder option, you must have
        the following files present:

           -- L:speak-handler

           -- LIBS:translator.library

           -- DEVS:narrator.device

           -- SYS:Utilities/Say

        Note that the above is the standard "speech" software
        distribution and placement for AmigaDOS 1.3 and 2.04.

        Commodore ceased distribution of these files beginning
        with AmigaDOS 2.1.

        If you have upgraded to AmigaDOS 2.1 and/or 3.0, you
        should be able to copy these files from your original
        AmigaDOS 1.3 and/or 2.04 distribution disks.

        Finally, the exact location of the "Say" program can
        be adjusted via the SAYLOCATION Tooltype (see "Icon
        Tooltypes").  That is, the "Say" program does NOT have
        to be in the SYS:Utilities directory.

@endnode

@node limitations "Limitations"

Limitations

      - Can only be used from the Workbench (start via Icon)

      - Only 1 reminder per program execution is supported

      - Once set, no method of canceling a reminder is provided

      - Previously set reminders do not survive system reboots

      - A maximum period of 24 hours is supported for both duration types

      - Reminder was developed on an A1200 and A4000 running AmigaDOS 3.0

        I do not have an AmigaDOS 2.04 or 2.1 system to test on

        Therefore, I cannot guarantee that the program will work
        100% correctly under 2.04 or 2.1 

        Please let me know if you have success using Reminder on either
        a 2.04 or 2.1-based system

@endnode

@node releasenotes "Release Notes"

Release Notes

      - Version 1.0 : Initial release.

      - Version 1.1 : Added spoken reminder functionality.

                      Reworked user interface given the preceding.

                      Changed "library version" minimum to include
                      AmigaDOS 2.04 and above.

                      Changed compilation/link CPU target to
                      "any CPU".

@endnode

@node why "Why did I create Reminder?"

Why did I create Reminder?

Like most people, when I'm working on the computer I tend to lose track
of time.  I found myself forgetting to do things, like make an important
phone call, catching a program I wanted to see, putting fabric softener
in the washing machine, (you get the drift).

I wasn't able to find any type of "timed reminder" tools were simple enough
to use on an ad-hoc basis.  I wanted something where I could easily set
up things like "remind me to check the washing machine in 10 minutes" or
"remind me to call Veronica at 8:30 PM".

Therefore, I created "Reminder".

@endnode

@node starting "Starting Reminder"

To start Reminder, click on the Reminder icon

Reminder will open it's window on the default Public Screen

Note that the Workbench screen is the standard default Public Screen

@endnode

@node windowdescription "Reminder Window Description"

The Reminder window consists of the following items:

  1) Time indicator
 
     Select which method of time specification you want to use
     for your reminder:

       - Elapsed  (output reminder so many hours/minutes/seconds
                   from now)

       - Specific (output reminder at a specific clock time,
                   specified in a standard "HH:MM AM/PM" format)

     The current time is placed in the time display when you first
     select the "Specific" type

  2) Time display (HH:MM:SS)

     Indicates the elapsed/specific time at which the reminder will
     be output

  3) AM/PM indicator

     Select whether the displayed HH:MM:SS is AM or PM
  
     Disabled when you select the "Elapsed" type

  4) Hrs/Mins/Secs sliders

     Use these to adjust the time display

     The Secs slider is disabled for the "Specific" type

  5) Type indicator

     Select the type of reminder you want to have output:

       - PopUp Only  (display reminder text in a pop-up window)

       - Speak Only  (speak reminder text using "Say" command)

       - Popup/Speak (both the above)

  5) ScreenFlash/NoScreenFlash indicator

     Specify whether you want the screen border to flash when
     the PopUp reminder is displayed

     Disabled with you select the "Speak Only" type.

  6) Male/Female/Natural/Monotone voice indicator

     Specify what "type" of voice you want used with your spoken
     reminder.

     Disabled with you select the "PopUp Only" type.

  7) Speed slider

     Adjust the speed of the voice used with your spoken reminder.

     Disabled with you select the "PopUp Only" type.

  8) Pitch slider

     Adjust the pitch of the voice used with your spoken reminder.

     Disabled with you select the "PopUp Only" type.

  8) Test button

     Speak the input "ReminderText", using the specified voice/speed/pitch.

     Very useful for checking out tuning values before committing your
     reminder.

     Also a lot of fun to just mess around with in general!

     Disabled with you select the "PopUp Only" type.

  9) ReminderText

     Specify the text you want displayed with your reminder

     REMEMBER TO HIT THE RETURN KEY ON YOUR KEYBOARD ONCE YOU'VE
     ENTERED THE TEXT!  THE PROGRAM WILL **NOT** SEE THE ENTERED
     TEXT UNTIL YOU DO!

 10) ? button

     Opens an info requestor

 11) Cancel button

     Quits the Reminder window - no reminder is established

     Note that quitting the window via the normal Intuition "window quit"
     button accomplishes the same thing

 12) Go button

     Commit the specified reminder, and remove the Reminder window

@endnode

@node basicptoperation "Basic Reminder Operation"

Reminder has been designed to be very easy to operate:

1) Indicate which type of time-duration you want to use: 

      - Elapsed  (display reminder text so many hours/minutes/seconds
                  from now)

      - Specific (display reminder text at a specific clock time,
                  specified in a standard "HH:MM AM/PM" format)

2) Set the elapsed/specific time using the Hrs/Mins/Secs sliders and
   the AM/PM indicator

3) Indicate which type of reminder you want output:

      - PopUp Only  (display reminder text in a pop-up window)

      - Speak Only  (speak reminder text using "Say" command)

      - Popup/Speak (both the above)

4) If you've selected "PopUp Only" or "PopUp/Speak", indicate whether 
   you want the screen border to flash when the actual Reminder window
   is displayed

5) If you've selected "Speak Only" or "PopUp/Speak", indicate the type
   of voice you want and the voice's Speed and Pitch.

6) Type the reminder text you want displayed into the "ReminderText"
   gadget

   REMEMBER TO HIT THE RETURN KEY ON YOUR KEYBOARD ONCE YOU'VE ENTERED
   THE TEXT!  THE PROGRAM WILL **NOT** SEE THE ENTERED TEXT UNTIL YOU DO!

7) If you've selected one of the "Speak" options, hear what your spoken
   reminder will sound like by selecting the "Test" button.

   Tweak the voice controls until you've got the values you want.

8) Select Go


Note that multiple reminders can be set up - just start the program again


After the specified time-duration, the "ReminderText" you specified
will be output (spoken and/or displayed in a window).

@endnode

@node icontooltypes "Icon Tooltypes"

Reminder recognizes the following Tooltypes within it's icon:

   X=<number>           -  The X-coordinate at which the Reminder window
                           will initially open

   Y=<number>           -  The Y-coordinate at which the Reminder window
                           will initially open

   SAYLOCATION=<path>   -  The full path to the "Say" command, excluding
                           the final "/"

                           Examples: SYS:Tools/Speech
                                     HD1:DosStuff


If these tooltypes are not present:

   - the Reminder window will open at coordinates X=10 Y=10

   - the "Say" command is assumed to be located in SYS:Utilities

@endnode

